00:14:27,833 --> 00:14:31,904
{\an8}<i>This is his first visit to Johnny's Shop
in 20 some years.</i>

237
00:14:32,538 --> 00:14:34,340
This brings back memories.

238
00:14:36,575 --> 00:14:37,943
Ah...

239
00:14:41,080 --> 00:14:43,482
There's TOKIO.

240
00:14:43,983 --> 00:14:45,651
Wow.

241
00:14:46,185 --> 00:14:48,587
Matsuoka was so cute.

242
00:14:49,755 --> 00:14:53,392
When I think of Matsuoka,
this is the image I think of.

243
00:14:53,959 --> 00:14:55,828
His cheeks were a little chubby.

244
00:14:56,695 --> 00:14:59,164
We were all rascals back then.

245
00:15:01,600 --> 00:15:03,402
Look at how unruly we were.

246
00:15:04,036 --> 00:15:05,504
Here too.

247
00:15:06,005 --> 00:15:07,640
And here too.

248
00:15:08,641 --> 00:15:11,777
Johnny's groups usually wear
colorful clothing on stage.

249
00:15:11,844 --> 00:15:14,780
People got mad and scolded us back then.

250
00:15:14,847 --> 00:15:16,048
Yeah.

251
00:15:16,115 --> 00:15:18,617
We relied on our seniors a lot too.

252
00:15:18,684 --> 00:15:23,255
They paid for our meals
and doted on us as junior members.

253
00:15:23,923 --> 00:15:25,457
The music that we played...

254
00:15:27,026 --> 00:15:30,829
had a lot of that mixed into it.

255
00:15:31,497 --> 00:15:33,632
It gave us the power to create something.

256
00:15:33,699 --> 00:15:35,701
Only the three of us could do that...

257
00:15:37,136 --> 00:15:38,804
It was our way of expression.

258
00:15:38,871 --> 00:15:42,841
How should I put this?

259
00:15:44,009 --> 00:15:48,981
It would be nice if we could find
a new way to express ourselves.

260
00:15:49,648 --> 00:15:52,117
Sorry for making you stay so late.

261
00:15:52,184 --> 00:15:53,652
Don't worry about it.

262
00:15:53,719 --> 00:15:55,587
I'd like a Matsuoka set, please.

263
00:15:55,654 --> 00:15:58,157
-Matsuoka's set?
-Yeah, the old one.

264
00:15:58,223 --> 00:16:00,826
-Would you like just his picture?
-Yes, of course.

265
00:16:00,893 --> 00:16:03,963
I'll hang it up somewhere in the company.

266
00:16:04,029 --> 00:16:05,731
This is nice.

267
00:16:09,735 --> 00:16:11,270
I'll be going now.

268
00:16:11,337 --> 00:16:12,571
Thank you so much.

269
00:16:15,674 --> 00:16:16,875
-See you later.
-Okay.

270
00:16:16,942 --> 00:16:19,645
-See you next time.
-Okay, goodnight.

271
00:16:24,049 --> 00:16:27,920
<i>Half a year has passed
since the company's activies began.</i>

272
00:16:30,756 --> 00:16:35,294
<i>They've been having many discussions
about the next project.</i>

273
00:16:45,771 --> 00:16:49,541
The first year of a company
is all about creating a foundation.

274
00:16:49,608 --> 00:16:51,877
What can we challenge ourselves to?

275
00:16:51,944 --> 00:16:53,645
All sorts of foundations.

276
00:16:53,712 --> 00:16:56,015
Foundations as a company.

277
00:16:56,081 --> 00:16:58,083
Foundations as an entertainer.

278
00:16:58,150 --> 00:16:59,685
Foundations as an individual.

279
00:16:59,752 --> 00:17:03,922
I'd love it if we could
expand each one of them.

280
00:17:06,558 --> 00:17:10,829
<i>The member have been clearing out
the different fields unique to them.</i>

281
00:17:12,431 --> 00:17:14,299
Mr. Kokubun, thank you for your time.

282
00:17:14,366 --> 00:17:16,902
Thank you for your call. This is Kokubun.

283
00:17:18,037 --> 00:17:22,941
<i>Kokubun is joining in
a TV station's broadcast program council.</i>

284
00:17:23,709 --> 00:17:28,280
<i>He has been asked his opinions
as an authority on creating TV programs.</i>

285
00:17:31,617 --> 00:17:34,987
<i>The issue for discussion today
is about a certain variety program.</i>

286
00:17:35,054 --> 00:17:38,390
...I believe I was able to
see a lot of that.

287
00:17:38,457 --> 00:17:41,660
If I'm to speak from
a presenter's point of view,

288
00:17:41,727 --> 00:17:45,030
I wouldn't want to be given
a specific format.

289
00:17:45,097 --> 00:17:50,869
I believe all the presenters
will want to create something on the spot.

290
00:17:50,936 --> 00:17:55,974
So I really liked how it was edited
to emphasize that this was happening.

291
00:17:56,041 --> 00:17:59,244
Here's the host, Mr. Shigeru Joshima.

292
00:18:00,312 --> 00:18:04,550
<i>Joshima will appear on a business program</i>

293
00:18:04,616 --> 00:18:07,086
<i>as TOKIO Inc.'s president.</i>

294
00:18:07,152 --> 00:18:10,456
Even if that's the case,
will we be able to reach that point?

295
00:18:10,522 --> 00:18:11,857
<i>In addition...</i>

296
00:18:12,724 --> 00:18:16,929
{\an8}"KOKORO NI HANA" MIXING

297
00:18:30,843 --> 00:18:32,010
Yay!

298
00:18:32,578 --> 00:18:33,645
Thank you.

299
00:18:33,712 --> 00:18:34,713
Thank you.

300
00:18:35,314 --> 00:18:41,353
Now you have to sing it in front of
the fans, share it, and then it's done.

301
00:18:41,420 --> 00:18:43,856
Or maybe songs don't end just like that.

302
00:18:44,423 --> 00:18:45,924
Maybe songs don't have an ending.

303
00:18:45,991 --> 00:18:49,061
Since songs are passed down
to the people that listen to it.

304
00:18:51,096 --> 00:18:55,667
{\an8}<i>Matsugoka goes onto
a new stage as an actor.</i>

305
00:18:55,734 --> 00:18:56,935
{\an8}DRAMA PRESS RELEASE

306
00:18:58,036 --> 00:19:01,473
It was an acting experience
that I have never had before.

307
00:19:01,540 --> 00:19:04,109
I have acted
in all sorts of things before,

308
00:19:04,176 --> 00:19:07,179
but I believe this one
has left an impression on my heart.

309
00:19:08,514 --> 00:19:10,883
<i>He talks to the director backstage.</i>

310
00:19:13,118 --> 00:19:15,787
<i>He's getting used to using smartphones.</i>

311
00:19:16,488 --> 00:19:17,523
<i>Toyama no Kin-san</i>.

312
00:19:19,525 --> 00:19:22,094
-I'll see you later.
-Thank you. See you later.

313
00:19:23,195 --> 00:19:24,163
Okay.

314
00:19:24,229 --> 00:19:25,497
-Thank you.
-Good work.

315
00:19:27,266 --> 00:19:32,971
Launching TOKIO Inc.
was the first step in our journey.

316
00:19:33,038 --> 00:19:37,776
And we're all middle aged men now.

317
00:19:39,578 --> 00:19:42,748
The president will be 60 in nine years.

318
00:19:43,315 --> 00:19:45,817
We don't want anyone
to be responsible for us

319
00:19:45,884 --> 00:19:47,786
and we don't want to be a big burden.

320
00:19:49,288 --> 00:19:51,256
How can I put this?

321
00:19:51,323 --> 00:19:55,394
If Shigeru Joshima can wear a red vest
and we can all laugh, it'll be okay.

322
00:19:55,460 --> 00:19:56,828
If we keep that atmosphere,

323
00:19:58,997 --> 00:20:01,533
I think we'll be able to do
something interesting.

324
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:02,868
I faintly feel that way.

325
00:20:04,203 --> 00:20:08,507
Our group has made it this far
after experiencing so many failures.

326
00:20:08,574 --> 00:20:13,011
"This time wasn't perfect,
so let's make the next one a success."

327
00:20:13,078 --> 00:20:17,049
TOKIO is just that kind of group
that repeats that cycle all the time.

328
00:20:17,115 --> 00:20:22,721
Having the quality to see people
for who and what they are

329
00:20:22,788 --> 00:20:27,392
is probably the biggest factor
to enjoy us as a group.

330
00:20:27,459 --> 00:20:31,797
I just love TOKIO as a group.

331
00:20:34,032 --> 00:20:37,302
It's difficult to continually
work hard on something...

332
00:20:38,136 --> 00:20:39,871
but it's important.

333
00:20:40,439 --> 00:20:42,774
No matter how much we change,

334
00:20:42,841 --> 00:20:45,410
I don't want to lose my home,
the place I belong.

335
00:20:46,878 --> 00:20:48,447
I love TOKIO.

336
00:20:48,513 --> 00:20:50,882
I'm objectively a fan.

337
00:20:54,319 --> 00:20:55,621
{\an8}Here we go.

338
00:20:56,154 --> 00:20:59,491
{\an8}<i>Masahiro Matsuoka, age 44.</i>

339
00:21:01,660 --> 00:21:04,963
{\an8}<i>Shigeru Joshima, age 51.</i>

340
00:21:06,732 --> 00:21:10,402
{\an8}<i>Taichi Kokubun, age 47.</i>

341
00:21:11,370 --> 00:21:13,238
{\an8}No way, no thanks!

342
00:21:13,305 --> 00:21:14,706
{\an8}I don't want to do that.

343
00:21:14,773 --> 00:21:16,775
{\an8}I don't want to put our backs together.

344
00:21:16,842 --> 00:21:19,678
{\an8}We're too old to be
doing something like that.

345
00:21:19,745 --> 00:21:20,912
{\an8}Ninety-seven years old.

346
00:21:25,050 --> 00:21:29,221
<i>Their story has just gotten started.</i>

347
00:21:32,090 --> 00:21:33,091
<i>Next time...</i>

348
00:21:34,259 --> 00:21:38,297
{\an8}<i>In 2021, there's a group of seven
that was able to debut.</i>

349
00:21:38,363 --> 00:21:39,665
{\an8}<i>Naniwa Danshi.</i>

350
00:21:40,766 --> 00:21:43,669
{\an8}<i>One month before their debut announcement...</i>

351
00:21:44,403 --> 00:21:45,237
BEFORE THEIR DEBUT

352
00:21:45,304 --> 00:21:48,073
I don't know how we'll be,
but how do you want to be?

353
00:21:48,140 --> 00:21:50,042
Naniwa Danshi in the future.

354
00:21:51,343 --> 00:21:54,246
<i>They talk about
what they should aim for as idols.</i>

355
00:21:55,914 --> 00:21:59,584
Like the pioneer of boy idols groups.

356
00:21:59,651 --> 00:22:01,653
I want to be a hero to everyone.

357
00:22:01,720 --> 00:22:03,622
To be acknowledged as an idol group.

358
00:22:03,689 --> 00:22:06,224
I think everything ends
once we realize our possibilities.

359
00:22:06,291 --> 00:22:07,726
We're here because of our fans.

360
00:22:07,793 --> 00:22:10,329
I want to do things
nobody has done before.

361
00:22:11,697 --> 00:22:14,833
<i>Backstage of Naniwa Danshi's debut.</i>

362
00:22:14,900 --> 00:22:16,902
